36:46.004 --> 36:51.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In this
campaign, the topic
of refugees from war-torn Syria
has been a

36:51.810 --> 36:53.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
political flash point.

36:53.511 --> 36:56.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We want to look at what it's
been like for
refugees themselves.

36:56.414 --> 37:01.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 2015, just under 1,700 Syrian
refugees
were resettled in the United
States.

37:02.020 --> 37:06.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This year, that number has shot
up to more
than 12,000, a significant
increase, but few

37:06.658 --> 37:12.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in comparison to Canada, which
has taken in
33,000 this year, or Europe,
which has absorbed

37:12.464 --> 37:16.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hundreds of thousands of people
fleeing the
war at home.

37:16.267 --> 37:19.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last year, special correspondent
Marcia Biggs
introduced us to one Syrian
family that arrived

37:19.604 --> 37:22.040 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the U.S. as part of that
first group.

37:22.073 --> 37:26.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She recently checked back in
with them amid
a difficult transition to life
here, and sent

37:26.444 --> 37:28.279 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
us this report.

37:28.313 --> 37:33.852 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA BIGGS: A typical
afternoon in this
New Jersey home, mom in the
kitchen, son reading

37:33.885 --> 37:38.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the sofa and preteen daughter
chatting
on her smartphone.

37:38.123 --> 37:43.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a mundane reality compared
to the horror
they have fled, a war zone in
Syria, overcrowded

37:43.862 --> 37:46.765 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
refugee camps in Jordan.

37:46.798 --> 37:49.567 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We first met the Darbi family
last year.

37:49.601 --> 37:56.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Newly arrived, they were five of
the roughly
1,700 Syrians resettled in the
U.S. in 2015,

37:56.708 --> 38:00.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
living with the help of grants
from the federal
government and Church World
Service, one of

38:00.979 --> 38:05.416 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
nine NGOs organizations
assisting refugee
resettlement, helping them find
housing and

38:05.450 --> 38:07.585 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
enroll in language classes.

38:07.619 --> 38:12.223 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For husband and wife Mohamed and
Amira, it
was the chance for a new life.

38:12.257 --> 38:15.527 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their three children were
starting the first
week of school.

38:15.560 --> 38:16.961 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Hope was in the air.

38:16.995 --> 38:18.830 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But today:

38:18.863 --> 38:21.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOHAMED DARBI, Resettled Syrian
Refugee (through
translator): I'm surprised that,
a year later,

38:21.666 --> 38:23.134 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm still in the same place.

38:23.168 --> 38:24.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In fact, I feel that I have gone
backwards.

38:24.903 --> 38:26.971 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I feel like, next year, I might
fail.

38:27.005 --> 38:30.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They should have given us more
time for school,
so that we could learn the
language.

38:30.808 --> 38:36.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Five months after
their arrival,
the financial assistance ended
and Mohamed

38:36.981 --> 38:39.717 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
struggled to find a steady job.

38:39.751 --> 38:44.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once a carpenter in Syria, he is
currently
doing manual labor at a
construction site,

38:44.923 --> 38:47.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
having abandoned language
classes.

38:48.026 --> 38:52.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Without a car, he cycles to job
sites and
barely makes enough to afford
this two-bedroom

38:52.897 --> 38:54.432 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
apartment.

38:54.465 --> 38:57.101 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Six-year-old Shaker (ph) sleeps
in his parents'
room.

38:57.135 --> 39:00.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: When was the last
time you spoke
to someone from Church World
Service?

39:00.572 --> 39:03.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MOHAMED DARBI (through
translator): It was
a long time ago.

39:03.841 --> 39:07.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the office, they treated us
as if we need
special connections for a simple
request.

39:07.579 --> 39:09.981 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How am I going to ask them for a
job?

39:10.014 --> 39:14.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: According to
Church World Service,
his frustration is typical of
refugees who

39:14.419 --> 39:18.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have high expectations and lack
understanding
of the concept of starting from
the ground

39:19.023 --> 39:20.091 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
up.

39:20.124 --> 39:22.026 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We spoke with Sarah Krause,
director of programs.

39:22.060 --> 39:24.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SARAH KRAUSE, Church World
Service: It's a
challenge to find something in
the refugee's

39:24.796 --> 39:26.064 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
chosen field.

39:26.097 --> 39:28.499 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's going to take a
little more time.

39:28.533 --> 39:30.702 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It also takes time to learn
English.

39:30.735 --> 39:36.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Oftentimes, in families, both
the husband
and the wife need to work in
order to really

39:36.074 --> 39:39.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
support the family, just as is
the case with
American families.

39:39.811 --> 39:45.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We receive a very limited amount
of money
to provide those initial
resettlement services.

39:45.984 --> 39:49.120 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's $2,025 per individual.

39:49.153 --> 39:53.258 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's not a lot of money to get
someone started
in the United States.

39:53.291 --> 39:58.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Just over 300
Syrian refugees
arrived in New Jersey in the
last year.

39:58.129 --> 40:02.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like the Darbi family, most of
them were resettled
here in the shadow of New York
City's Freedom

40:02.867 --> 40:04.802 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Tower.

40:04.836 --> 40:08.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But some people argue that
placing them here
may have actually hurt their
chances for integration.

40:08.039 --> 40:12.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOHAMED KHAIRULLAH, Mayor of
Prospect Park,
New Jersey: Most of the Syrian
refugees that

40:12.043 --> 40:18.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are coming into New Jersey are
being settled
in either Jersey City or
Elizabeth, which

40:18.383 --> 40:24.422 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
really doesn't have any Syrian
community there.

40:24.455 --> 40:27.825 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Mohamed Khairullah
is also a
Syrian refugee.

40:27.859 --> 40:33.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Born in Aleppo, he was just a
child in 1980
when his family fled a crackdown
by Bashar

40:33.698 --> 40:36.134 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
al-Assad's father, Hafez.

40:36.167 --> 40:42.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He emigrated to the U.S. in
1991, settling
in Prospect Park, New Jersey,
about 20 miles

40:42.440 --> 40:43.941 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
from the Darbis.

40:43.975 --> 40:47.211 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's been mayor here for over a
decade.

40:47.245 --> 40:52.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He believes that resettling
refugees in Arab
neighborhoods like his would
provide a support

40:52.116 --> 40:56.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
network, and make finding them
the right job
and getting them into English
classes easier.

40:56.721 --> 41:01.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOHAMED KHAIRULLAH: Most of
them, you speak
to them and they say, listen, we
want to work,

41:01.259 --> 41:02.994 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we want to provide for our
families.

41:03.027 --> 41:06.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't want to go from one
organization
to another, asking for help.

41:06.898 --> 41:08.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's humiliating to us.

41:08.733 --> 41:13.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And these private organizations
need to speak
to us, need to communicate with
us, need to

41:13.971 --> 41:18.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
let us know ahead of time when
there is a
refugee family coming in, so we
could try

41:18.109 --> 41:21.679 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to find a home for them in our
areas.

41:21.713 --> 41:26.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: While the Darbis
say their neighbors
are friendly, not one of them is
Arab, and

41:26.317 --> 41:28.619 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the family has very little
interaction with
them.

41:28.653 --> 41:31.389 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do you have any kind of a
support network?

41:31.422 --> 41:33.024 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If there is an emergency, who do
you call?

41:33.057 --> 41:35.493 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MOHAMED DARBI (through
translator): There
is no one.

41:35.526 --> 41:38.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: The children are
their ray of
hope.

41:38.663 --> 41:44.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last year, then 11-year-old
Hajar and 13-year-old
Nabiha couldn't speak a lick of
English.

41:44.535 --> 41:45.703 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But this year:

41:45.737 --> 41:46.704 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What's your favorite music?

41:46.738 --> 41:48.072 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What do you dance to?

41:48.106 --> 41:49.640 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NABIHA DARBI, Resettled Syrian
Refugee: "Rolling
in the Deep."

41:49.674 --> 41:50.641 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA BIGGS: Adele?

41:50.675 --> 41:51.642 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You like Adele?

41:51.676 --> 41:52.643 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NABIHA DARBI: Yes.

41:52.677 --> 41:54.479 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: One other change
we noticed?

41:54.512 --> 41:58.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hajar began wearing a hijab,
something she
says she was proud to do when
she turned 12

41:58.716 --> 42:02.787 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
years old, and a decision her
parents say
she made on her own.

42:02.820 --> 42:05.056 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MOHAMED DARBI (through
translator): I felt
that she was still young.

42:05.089 --> 42:06.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I told her maybe you should
wait.

42:06.724 --> 42:07.992 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But she insisted.

42:08.025 --> 42:10.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Do you know why
she wanted to
wear it earlier?

42:10.061 --> 42:12.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMIRA DARBI, Resettled Syrian
Refugee (through
translator): Maybe it was
because, after she

42:12.930 --> 42:17.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
started school here in the
States, she wanted
to show people her culture and
traditions.

42:17.602 --> 42:21.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: The girls say they
have been
bullied in school, often because
of their

42:21.873 --> 42:23.641 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
religion.

42:23.674 --> 42:25.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HAJAR DARBI, Resettled Syrian
Refugee (through
translator): I didn't just wear
the hijab

42:25.410 --> 42:26.911 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
because I have to.

42:26.944 --> 42:29.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was because kids at school
were telling
my sister to take off her hijab.

42:30.014 --> 42:32.950 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They were telling her that this
is America
and we don't wear hijab here.

42:32.984 --> 42:36.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A few weeks later, I started
wearing the hijab
and the kids at school started
asking me,

42:36.621 --> 42:38.456 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are you Muslim, are you Muslim?

42:38.489 --> 42:40.057 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I said, yes, I am Muslim.

42:40.091 --> 42:41.959 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's nobody's business but mine.

42:41.993 --> 42:45.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Even with these
obstacles, the
girls say they are happy in
school, love their

42:46.030 --> 42:48.332 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
teachers, and their classes.

42:48.366 --> 42:52.503 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hajar still wants to be a
doctor, but Nabiha
says she wants to be an artist.

42:52.537 --> 42:54.372 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do you feel like you're home
here?

42:54.405 --> 42:55.506 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HAJAR DARBI: Yes.

42:55.540 --> 42:57.041 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA BIGGS: You do?

42:57.074 --> 43:00.812 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HAJAR DARBI: And our future is
here, not in
Syria.

43:00.845 --> 43:05.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Those are very big
words for
a young girl, and for Nabiha,
who has more

43:05.450 --> 43:08.386 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
memories of Syria, it's much
more complicated.

43:08.419 --> 43:10.321 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NABIHA DARBI: I don't know.

43:10.354 --> 43:12.290 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is a good country.

43:12.323 --> 43:13.324 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And I like it.

43:13.357 --> 43:21.399 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If there is no war in Syria, I
will come back.

43:21.432 --> 43:25.803 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But I will visit this country.

43:25.837 --> 43:33.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't know in which country I
would be better,
because my family, some of them
in Turkey,

43:33.544 --> 43:36.180 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
some of it in Syria, and some of
it in Jordan.

43:36.214 --> 43:38.616 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I want all of them in one
country.

43:38.649 --> 43:44.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Her English
doesn't suffice
to describe the painful
separation of displacement.

43:44.522 --> 43:50.461 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NABIHA DARBI (through
translator): I am used
to having them around ever since
I was a child.

43:50.495 --> 43:55.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If I can't see them, I don't
think I can carry
on in this life.

43:55.433 --> 43:57.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Every member of my family is in
a different
country.

43:57.635 --> 44:03.875 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I can't even comprehend this.

44:03.908 --> 44:17.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: The family also
arrived in one
of the most politically
polarizing times in

44:17.421 --> 44:23.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
recent U.S. history, with parts
of that conflict
surrounding both Syrian refugees
and Islam,

44:23.961 --> 44:29.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
New Jersey Governor Chris
Christie shutting
the door on Syrian refugees in
his state,

44:29.467 --> 44:34.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump calling for a
temporary ban on
all Muslims entering the U.S.
and making so-

44:34.772 --> 44:38.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
called extreme vetting of
refugees a campaign
issue.

44:38.276 --> 44:41.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate:
And we now have them in our
country, and wait

44:41.045 --> 44:42.013 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
until you see.

44:42.046 --> 44:43.915 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is going to be the great
Trojan horse.

44:43.948 --> 44:47.184 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MOHAMED DARBI (through
translator): He's talking
about a plan he doesn't know
anything about.

44:47.218 --> 44:50.121 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It took a whole year of vetting
before we
were allowed to come here.

44:50.154 --> 44:52.423 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Does he want a 10-year vetting
process?

44:52.456 --> 44:54.926 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The war would be over by then.

44:54.959 --> 44:57.094 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We didn't come to America with
any bad intentions.

44:57.128 --> 44:58.996 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We came here asking for safety.

44:59.030 --> 45:01.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
If our country weren't
completely destroyed,
we wouldn't have left.

45:01.799 --> 45:04.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: How do those
comments make you
feel?

45:04.602 --> 45:08.906 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MOHAMED DARBI (through
translator): I feel
like an innocent man in jail for
a crime I

45:08.940 --> 45:09.907 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
didn't commit.

45:09.941 --> 45:11.642 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I feel frustrated.

45:11.676 --> 45:15.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I keep asking myself, is it
possible that
some people here might think
this way?

45:15.446 --> 45:17.014 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
When I think of Americans, they
are innovators.

45:17.048 --> 45:18.583 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They reached the moon.

45:18.616 --> 45:20.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But with this type of thinking,
you can't
reach the moon.

45:20.985 --> 45:23.354 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: So, have we
disappointed you?

45:23.387 --> 45:25.590 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MOHAMED DARBI (through
translator): No.

45:25.623 --> 45:28.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm telling you, the American
people do not
disappoint me.

45:28.292 --> 45:31.963 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, as the saying goes, the
politicians are
throwing gasoline on a fire.

45:31.996 --> 45:36.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Despite the
difficulties, the
Darbis remain grateful, even
hospitable.

45:36.934 --> 45:40.871 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MOHAMED DARBI (through
translator): The children
have become safe and secure, and
now they

45:40.905 --> 45:41.906 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
have a future.

45:41.939 --> 45:44.275 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It means they are living a
normal life.

45:44.308 --> 45:45.476 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm beyond exhausted.

45:45.509 --> 45:47.044 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I was expecting better.

45:47.078 --> 45:49.513 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But when it comes to normal
life, it's wonderful.

45:49.547 --> 45:53.751 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: A normal life and
a hope for
a better tomorrow.

45:53.784 --> 45:58.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Marcia Biggs in
Jersey City, New Jersey.

45:58.155 --> 46:02.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
